A July 2019 NYT job ad for Nairobi bureau chief is chock full of clich√©s about
Africa referencing the ‚Äúshores of Tanzania‚Äù and the ‚Äúdeserts of Sudan.‚Äù Photo
of a dhow passing on the Indian Ocean in Tanzania, by Pernille Baerendtsen,
used with permission.

On July 3, 2019, the New York Times announced a [job
ad](https://www.linkedin.com/jobs/view/nairobi-bureau-chief-at-the-new-york-
times-1332110667/?originalSubdomain=ke&fbclid=IwAR0f2KExCDtnOu6n-9zSotlZ-N0MkTHXO9WWFyAVmVK7ZIrF0Z6KF7Cs2a4)
in search of the next bureau chief for its Nairobi, Kenya, office. The
reductive language used to describe the ideal candidate‚Äôs role and
responsibilities has reignited the debate on Western media's trafficking of
tired stereotypes about Africa.

The first few lines of the ad states:

> Our Nairobi bureau chief has a tremendous opportunity to dive into news and
> enterprise across a wide range of countries, from the deserts of Sudan and
> the pirate seas of the Horn of Africa, down through the forests of Congo and
> the shores of Tanzania.

Many who read it had to stop there ‚Äî ‚Äúfrom the deserts of Sudan and the pirate
seas of the Horn of Africa ‚Ä¶?‚Äù Netizens on Twitter began to comment
immediately about how the author of this ad had taken instructions from ‚Äú[How
To Write About Africa](https://granta.com/how-to-write-about-africa/),‚Äù by the
[late Kenyan writer Binyavanga
Wainaina](https://globalvoices.org/2019/05/23/kenyan-writer-binyavanga-
wainaina-who-taught-the-world-how-to-write-about-africa-dies-at-48/) ‚Äî without
getting the memo that he was being sarcastic.

But it doesn‚Äôt stop:

> It is an enormous patch of vibrant, intense and strategically important
> territory with many vital story lines, including terrorism, the scramble for
> resources, the global contest with China and the constant push-and-pull of
> democracy versus authoritarianism.

East Africa, described as an ‚Äúenormous patch‚Äù? A region reduced to ‚Äúvital
storylines‚Äù such as ‚Äúterrorism, the scramble for resources, the global contest
with China?‚Äù Netizens pointed out that the ad clearly relies on [tired,
colonial-era](https://citizentv.co.ke/news/unexpected-stories-of-hope-new-
york-times-nairobi-boss-advert-slammed-by-
kot-262211/?fbclid=IwAR3Vt_oQS3l2FYo6g4wZ2smoFDkJTLZSLmdVbu7F85F6J84hTZdkyS27AXk)
tropes about Africa:

> The [@nytimes](https://twitter.com/nytimes?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw) advertised
> the following vacancy for a
> [#Nairobi](https://twitter.com/hashtag/Nairobi?src=hash&ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw)
> Bureau Chief position. If we wouldn‚Äôt know better you would think it was
> written by a colonial master that never left. Colonialism is still around in
> a big way, under various guises. Let
> [#Africa](https://twitter.com/hashtag/Africa?src=hash&ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw)
