> PRESIDENT.

### NYT history in Kenya

The NYT is not new to pushback in Nairobi in its handling of stories from the
region.

When a deadly terrorist attack struck the Dusit Hotel in Riverside in Nairobi
in January 2019, killing 15 and wounding over 30, then-incoming bureau chief,
Kimiko de Freytas-Tamura, wrote a controversial [article
](https://www.nytimes.com/2019/01/15/world/africa/nairobi-attack.html?smid=tw-
nytimes&smtyp=cur)about it for the NYT, which featured graphic photos of slain
victims covered with blood.

The images invoked local and global fury for being insensitive, inappropriate
and [dishonorable.](https://theconversation.com/why-photographs-of-dead-in-
nairobi-terror-attack-failed-journalism-and-dishonoured-victims-110010) Many
also called out the double standard that led to publishing these images,
suggesting that had the victims been white, the NYT would not have published
them.

Kenyans on Twitter, or [#KOT](https://twitter.com/hashtag/KOT?src=hash), first
waged their collective rage directly at de Freytas-Tamura, calling for her
resignation and deportation. But de Freytas-Tamura pointed to the NYT‚Äôs photo
department who approved the photos.

Kenya‚Äôs Media Council gave the NYT [24
hours](https://www.npr.org/2019/01/17/686144953/in-bad-taste-disrespectful-
photo-of-terror-attack-in-kenya-sparks-controversy) to [take down the
article](https://twitter.com/MediaCouncilK/status/1085869526032531457) and
photos from their website, but the newspaper did not budge ‚Äî or apologize:

> [@mediacouncilk](https://twitter.com/MediaCouncilK?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw)
> today officially wrote a protest note to
> [@nytimes](https://twitter.com/nytimes?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw) over it's
> coverage of
> [#riversideattack](https://twitter.com/hashtag/riversideattack?src=hash&ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw)
> [pic.twitter.com/w27B20f73W](https://t.co/w27B20f73W)
>
> ‚Äî Media Council of Kenya (@MediaCouncilK) [January 17,
> 2019](https://twitter.com/MediaCouncilK/status/1085869526032531457?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw)

The NYT responded:

> We have heard from some readers upset with our publishing a photo showing
> victims after a brutal attack in Nairobi. We understand how painful this
> coverage can be, and we try to be very sensitive in how we handle both words
> and images in these situations. <https://t.co/Qjm0qBMaF3>
> [pic.twitter.com/1sqgTnnVKW](https://t.co/1sqgTnnVKW)
>
> ‚Äî The New York Times (@nytimes) [January 15,
> 2019](https://twitter.com/nytimes/status/1085271834709368834?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw)

Kenyans [reacted](https://theconversation.com/why-photographs-of-dead-in-
nairobi-terror-attack-failed-journalism-and-dishonoured-victims-110010) so
strongly against de Freytas-Tamura ‚Äî even threatening her life ‚Äî that the NYT
eventually shifted de Freytas-Tamura back to the London office. She never did
assume her role officially as Nairobi bureau chief ‚Äî and the controversial
photos remain online.

### ‚ÄòLove, Africa‚Äô

Another former NYT Nairobi bureau chief, award-winning journalist Jeffrey
Gettleman, also raised eyebrows with his recent book ‚ÄúLove, Africa.‚Äù The book
cover depicts the [classic tree and sunset](https://qz.com/207527/the-reason-
every-book-about-africa-has-the-same-cover-and-its-not-pretty/) and speaks to
colonial overtones and fascination with ‚Äúothering‚Äù Africa.

In a [review](http://aidnography.blogspot.com/2017/09/love-africa-romance-war-
survival-jeffrey-gettleman-book-review.html) of Gettleman‚Äôs book, German
anthropologist, Tobias Denskus, concludes:

> On further reflection, ‚Ä¶ his narrative seems a bit outdated, maybe even out
> of touch with the changing realities around him and the expectations from
> privileged global professionals.

### Kenyans reclaim narratives on social media

Kenyans on Twitter do not only target the NYT. Several other examples point to
moments when Kenyan Twitter came out to admonish and correct offensive
language that perpetuates tropes and stereotypes about Africa.

In 2012, when Korean Airways launched Nairobi as a destination, it
[released](https://www.capitalfm.co.ke/news/2012/06/kenyans-full-of-primitive-
energy/) an advert that said: ‚ÄúFly Korean Air and enjoy the grand African
Savanna, the safari tour, and the indigenous people full of primitive energy.‚Äù
The [advert ](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3PJbVSdrFns)went [viral
](https://www.capitalfm.co.ke/news/2012/06/kenyans-full-of-primitive-
energy/)and unleashed a flood of tweets calling for Korean Air to reconsider
flying to Kenya.

In 2015, when CNN labeled Kenya [‚Äúa hotbed of
terror‚Äù](https://www.independent.co.uk/news-19-0/someonetellcnn-kenyans-
ridicule-us-network-on-twitter-for-hotbed-of-terror-report-10410337.html)
ahead of United States President Barack Obama‚Äôs visit, over 75,000 tweets
within a single day protested the stereotype.[
](https://www.independent.co.uk/news-19-0/someonetellcnn-kenyans-ridicule-us-
network-on-twitter-for-hotbed-of-terror-report-10410337.html)

### The dark continent?

Perhaps the NYT is numb to loud reactions. The new ad clearly falls into the
old ‚Äúdark continent‚Äù trap.

Seven years after Welsh 19th century explorer, [Henry Morton
Stanley](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henry_Morton_Stanley), cast Africa as
‚Äú[the dark continent](https://www.wdl.org/en/item/7770/)‚Äù ‚Äî based on
[travels](https://www.wdl.org/en/item/7770/) to Central and East Africa that
resulted in a published 1878 travelogue, ‚ÄúIn Darkest Africa‚Äù ‚Äî the [Berlin
Congress](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Congress_of_Berlin) divided up Africa
for ‚ÄúEuropean powers‚Äô [pleasure and
profit](https://www.jstor.org/stable/4620852?seq=1#page_scan_tab_contents).‚Äù

Africa as a ‚Äúdark continent‚Äù still persists in current Western mainstream
media imaginations.

When University of Stanford media scholar, Toussaint Nothias,
[analysed](https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/1461670X.2016.1262748)
over 282 articles published in British and French newspapers between 2007 and
2012, he identified a systematic portrayal of Africa with ‚Äúdarkness‚Äù and
‚Äútribalism‚Äù that treated Africa as a ‚Äúhomogenous entity‚Äù with coverage that
relies ‚Äúpredominantly on Western sources.‚Äù

Cameroonian historian and philosopher, Achille Mbembe, uses the term[
‚Äúabsolute
otherness‚Äù](https://link.springer.com/referenceworkentry/10.1007%2F978-3-030-04941-6_8-1)
to describe how the West positions itself toward Africa. What Africa is ‚Äî the
West is not. The need to negate and contrast brightness with darkness still
dominates the West‚Äôs perception of its relationship with the other.

Let‚Äôs try to imagine the reverse, Jim Chuchu suggests:

> Let's imagine the reverse: ‚ÄúAfrican news agency seeking correspondents to
> cover America: a vibrant territory with many vital storylines, including
> inexplicable gun laws, the global contest with China, and a penchant for
> overthrowing foreign governments for sport‚Äù.
>
> ‚Äî Jim Chuchu (@jimchuchu) [July 4,
> 2019](https://twitter.com/jimchuchu/status/1146727194414276608?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw)

Chibuke Oguh, a Nigerian scholar, [argues
](https://www.researchgate.net/publication/292141961_The_Representation_of_Africa_in_Western_Media_still_a_21st_century_problem)that
this kind of framing ignores the continent‚Äôs many historical as well as
contemporary ‚Äúpolitical and economic success stories.‚Äù

Communicating these anachronistic ideas about Africa makes satire relevant ‚Äî
but it still doesn‚Äôt answer why the NYT got this so wrong.

